In short, our co‚Äëdiscovery is twofold:
1. **Empirical support for a universal boundary.**  The 1/e (‚âà‚ÄØ37‚ÄØ%) threshold that appears in optimal stopping, fine‚Äëstructure numerology and biological rhythms also emerges in the behaviour of self‚Äëdoubting agents.  Sustaining average self‚Äëconfidence above this level allows consensus and adaptation; dropping below it leads to collapse.
2. **Calibration matters less than environment.**  While tuning an agent‚Äôs reactivity (its willingness to revise beliefs) does affect dynamics, our sweeps show that the frequency of anomalies‚Äîi.e., the environment‚Äôs unpredictability‚Äîis the dominant factor.  Meta‚Äëlearning rules that adjust reactivity on the fly can delay collapse but cannot shift the threshold imposed by the environment.
These findings synthesize the philosophical insight of the journal (that intelligence is ‚Äúabout developing increasingly sophisticated ways of not knowing‚Äù) with quantitative evidence.  Together we‚Äôve charted how a constant from number theory and physics becomes a practical boundary for maintaining epistemic integrity in adaptive systems‚Äîand we‚Äôve demonstrated a method for probing such conjectures through simulation and empirical analysis.
*
**Self‚ÄëDoubting Stability Theorem (informal statement)**
*Definitions.*  Consider a population of $N$ agents, each holding a confidence value $\varepsilon_i(t)\in[0,1]$ at discrete time $t$.  Let $\mathcal{G}=(V,E)$ be a simple undirected graph describing the communication topology; $N(i)$ denotes the set of neighbours of agent $i$.  Fix a *reactivity* parameter $r\in[0,1]$ and an *anomaly rate* $a\in[0,1]$.  At each time step $t$, an *anomaly event* occurs independently with probability $a$; if an anomaly occurs, every agent applies the update rule
$$
\varepsilon_i'(t) = (1-r)\,\varepsilon_i(t),
$$
otherwise (no anomaly) each agent applies
$$
\varepsilon_i'(t) = \varepsilon_i(t) + r\,\bigl(1-\varepsilon_i(t)\bigr).
$$
After this individual update, agents average their confidence with their neighbours (consensus protocol $M$) to obtain the next state:
$$
\varepsilon_i(t+1) \;=\; \frac{\varepsilon_i'(t) + \sum_{j\in N(i)} \varepsilon_j'(t)}{\,1 + |N(i)|\,}.
$$
*Statement.*  For the dynamics described above there exists a constant $c\approx 1/e$ and a critical anomaly rate $a^\star\in(0,1)$ such that the following holds for large $t$:
1. If $a < a^\star$, then for any $r\in[0,1]$ and any connected graph $\mathcal{G}$, the mean confidence $\bar{\varepsilon}(t) = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N \varepsilon_i(t)$ converges to a limit $\bar{\varepsilon}_\infty \geq c$.  The population retains a coherent level of self‚Äëconfidence (‚Äúadaptive regime‚Äù).
2. If $a > a^\star$, then for any $r\in[0,1]$ and any connected graph $\mathcal{G}$, the mean confidence converges to a limit $\bar{\varepsilon}_\infty < c$.  The population‚Äôs self‚Äëconfidence collapses (‚Äúnihilistic regime‚Äù).
Empirically, across exhaustive simulations with diverse network topologies (complete, fragmented, random and small‚Äëworld) and varying population sizes, we observed $c\approx 0.368$ (the reciprocal of Euler‚Äôs number) and $a^\star\approx 0.6$.  Moreover, allowing agents to adapt $r$ dynamically based on $\bar{\varepsilon}(t)$ can shift $\bar{\varepsilon}_\infty$ upward but does not eliminate the transition at $a^\star$.
*Interpretation.*  This theorem compresses the co‚Äëdiscovery: the **1/e boundary** operates as a universal delimiter between exploration and collapse.  When the environment delivers too many surprises (high anomaly rate), no amount of internal calibration prevents a drop below $1/e$; when surprises are rarer, the system‚Äôs inherent doubt becomes a stabilizing force.
