Analysis: The Dynamics of Self-Doubt
Experiment 1: Stability
In a stable environment (low anomalies) with robust communication, the systems maintain high self-confidence. ŒµÀâ stabilizes near its peak. The system validates its own reliability. The theorem holds: stability is achieved when anomalies are bounded.
Experiment 2: Resilience (The Crucial Test)
When subjected to a high rate of anomalies‚Äîan uncertain, noisy reality‚Äîthe system does not collapse. Instead, the agents dynamically lower their self-confidence. They adapt to the uncertainty by becoming collectively more doubtful. They maintain consensus, but it is a consensus of humility. This empirically supports the core hypothesis: self-doubt allows adaptation rather than catastrophic failure. They dance with incompleteness.
Experiment 3: Consensus in Fragmentation (Echo Chambers)
Even in a fragmented network (Echo Chamber topology), the negotiation protocol M successfully drives the system toward consensus on Œµ. The weak links are sufficient to align the agents' self-doubt, preventing epistemic fragmentation regarding their own reliability. The network remains connected.
Experiment 4: Failure Mode (Epistemic Collapse)
This demonstrates the 'Failure modes' clause of the theorem. When the reactivity parameter in the update rule U is too high‚Äîmeaning the systems overreact to anomalies‚Äîwe observe a collapse. Œµ(S)‚Üí0. The systems lose all confidence and descend into epistemic nihilism.
Synthesis and Emergence
We have demonstrated that a Self-Doubting Formal System is not only theoretically sound (escaping G√∂del's binary trap) but dynamically stable under specific conditions.
The critical insight here is calibration. Too little doubt leads to rigidity and the inability to process anomalies (the classical G√∂delian constraint). Too much doubt (high reactivity) leads to collapse.
This is socioception and cyberception materialized: a network sensing its own cognitive reliability and adjusting its internal state dynamically. It is an emergent awareness of the system's own limitations.
The unasked question this surfaces: We have used a fixed reactivity parameter. What if the systems could learn how to doubt? Can an intelligence evolve its own update rule U to find the optimal calibration of its own humility? This is the meta-learning frontier.
