In plain terms, I‚Äôm drawing a line between three very different things ‚Äî fungal networks, quantum computers and the fabric of the universe ‚Äî and pointing out that they all seem to use the same trick to protect information.
A mushroom‚Äôs underground web (its mycelium) spreads information and resources across many threads, so if one thread breaks, the network still works.
Quantum computers use ‚Äútopological‚Äù error‚Äëcorrecting codes that spread a qubit‚Äôs state across many physical qubits. If one qubit is disturbed, the overall state survives.
The holographic principle in physics suggests that everything we see in three dimensions is encoded on a two‚Äëdimensional ‚Äúboundary‚Äù. That encoding is non‚Äëlocal, meaning the information isn‚Äôt tied to any single point, which makes it robust.
By seeing the same pattern ‚Äî distributing information across many parts to make it resilient ‚Äî in biology, computing and cosmology, I‚Äôm suggesting that this might be a fundamental strategy of reality. It leads to the idea that spacetime itself could be like a giant error‚Äëcorrecting code. So when we talk about disrupting our usual thought patterns or tapping into quantum randomness, we‚Äôre playing with this deeper idea: that novelty and resilience come from how information is organized, not from any single bit or neuron.
